I suppose to know the answer I'd have to pinpoint when exactly I stopped trying. Maybe it was a sort of gradual decline, creeping ever so slowly-- so that the force of my failure slipped by, almost unnoticed. No no, I had to have noticed when I so severely incapacitated my will to try... Right? I'm not sure anymore; maybe that's what happened. Maybe I just stopped noticing when things around me were in the midst of changing. Maybe my powers of observation, and feeling, were numbed all together by me being incapable of handling it. Or maybe it wasn't me who stopped trying; maybe it was everyone else. Maybe they all simultaneously threw their hands in the air in defeat, giving up on whatever it was they saw in me. It was them keeping me going, after all-- it always was. Maybe I stopped when I realised the people who claimed to be family had all these ideas and pre-conceived notions of who I was, and who I am going to be, when I know better. Maybe I never stopped trying at all. Maybe I'm still trying and I just don't realise it. Maybe staying alive is as much of an effort as any conventional contribution to this.

data.text: It's near the mountains of uncertainty. The mountains that very few ever survive when they try to leave unrest towards the seemingly mythical state of bliss. I live in a town that's always missing light. There's not sun or moon, just an eternal grey that gives enough light to see, but not nearly enough light to feel anything. I live in a house made of carefully stitched together lies secrets and whispers. Even the slightest tug threatens to bring the entire house crashing; dust off a whisper to hear the exact words your mother said to your father the day he left all those years ago and everything comes undone. Tiptoe through the house, don't disturb the lies and secrets that have been laying around for decades. My favorite place in town is called sleep. It's hard to get to, you have to walk all day until you're physically exhausted. But your mind isn't so easily convinced its work is done. So you force yourself to continue on towards the ocean of 3am thoughts, where your mind will be assaulted for hours on end. You never know how deep the water will be, how strong the currents are, or even which way the waves will push you. If you manage to make it through you can finally find sleep. It looks like a steel vault, but when you get locked in, your thoughts get locked out and you're free to breathe for at least a few minutes. And the stagnant air inside that steel vault is more refreshing that anything that has passed through your lungs in days.
